                                    <ul style="padding: 0; margin: 0; list-style-type: disc;">
										<li style="margin:0 0 10px 30px;" class="list-item-first"> Students and Postdocs, Karen from Goodman Research Group has asked me to remind you to complete the survey she has sent you. Your response will help us understand whether we are achieving our BPC goals, and how we can improve SPLICE offerings. If you can not find it, please email Karen (<a href="mailto:gareis@grginc.com">gareis@grginc.com</a>) so that she can send you your personalized link. As a reminder, your individual responses to the survey Karen sent out will <b>not</b> be viewed by anybody on the SPLICE team (that includes professors, postdocs, other students, and me). Karen and her team at Goodman Research Group, our external evaluators, will have access to your responses. If there are general trends in the responses, Karen will share those with SPLICE leadership. So, please be as candid as you are comfortable in your responses. If you choose to share feedback that includes identifiable information, and Karen and her team at GRG find that it is something that SPLICE leadership should be aware of, she will reach out to you privately to ensure any information sent to SPLICE leadership can be reframed to be un-identifiable or is shared with your consent.
                                        </li>
										<li style="margin:0 0 10px 30px"> A note from Nathan Reitinger (UMD): Data breaches are a problem that hardly needs an introduction—I’ve lost count of how many letters I’ve received informing me that, yet again, my data has been stolen in a breach. To help address this problem, we created the Breach Notification Database, a public-facing dataset (public querying pending, but ask me for internal access) that is the result of several years of information gathering on nine states posting public information about what data breaches have affected residents in their state &#40;e.g., New Hampshire lists breaches <a href="https://www.doj.nh.gov/citizens/consumer-protection-antitrust-bureau/security-breach-notifications">here</a>&#41;. States currently include California, Indiana, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Montana, New Hampshire, Texas, and Washington. Our information spans the company breached, the industry type of that company, a text-parsed letter that typically accompanies breach reports, and many other details like what was stolen and how the attack was initiated. We will use our dataset to measure how data breaches affect the United States. We will also conduct interviews with employees at companies that have been breached to add a behind-the-scenes look at what happens during a data breach. Our website, which summarizes the project, can be found <a href="https://bndb.umiacs.umd.edu/">here</a>. Let me know if you’d like more information or access to the data! We’d absolutely love it if others started using our resource &#128522  </li>
                                        <li style="margin:0 0 10px 30px">Check out the #general channel in the SPLICE workspace to find a list of various research resources provided by NSF! There might be something there that can aid your projects. </li>
                                        <li style="margin:0 0 10px 30px;"class="list-item-last"> All, the <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1s3QyJBL7T4Ihu62yavzfAbN2F_kr0Aloap2iA5pSRHA/edit?tab=t.0">SPLICE Annual Progress Report</a> is due June 1, 2025! Students and Postdocs, you are expected to fill out the form and review it with your advisor <i>before </i> June 1. Read the instructions at the top of the document for more details. <b>Pro Tip:</b> Where appropriate, you can word-for-word copy your bullet points from your monthly stand-up slides! All stand-up slide decks can be found in <a href="https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1yLLMLLL76uujFx0GiWz2FnML3eqbw6E9?usp=share_link">this folder</a>. </li>
